SIMPLE: motto
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Motto
<hw>Mot"to</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Mottoes</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[It. <ets>motto</ets> a
word, a saying, L. <ets>muttum</ets> a mutter, a grunt, cf.
<ets>muttire</ets>, <ets>mutire</ets>, to mutter, mumble; prob. of
imitative origin. Cf. <er>Mot</er> a word.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>A sentence, phrase, or word, forming part of an
heraldic achievment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A sentence, phrase, or word, prefixed to an essay,
discourse, chapter, canto, or the like, suggestive of its subject
matter; a short, suggestive expression of a guiding principle; a
maxim.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It was the <qex>motto</qex> of a bishop eminent for his piety and
good works, . . . ⟦ldquo⟧Serve God, and be cheerful.⟦rdquo⟧</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mottoed</ent>⟦br⟧
